@nftgoodguy Yikes.

Also I want to clarify the "guarantee of value" part. There is never a guarantee. We all signed up for that uncertainty when we entered this space. But there are things that can be done on behalf of these "teams" to place the project in a beneficial position for it's holders.

It is an insult to our intelligence and our community. I do not care if you think it can make you a little bit of ETH. If we do not do something about it now, it'll never end. This space is already riddled with greedy people who have our worst, yet their best intentions in mind.

And since when do we ever pay loads of ETH up front for a product we have barely even seen and has no guarantee of value? These lazy, rushed, expensive mints from teams with no track record or reputation need to stop. You need to be willing to sacrifice for this anon.

Every single time we buy a project that has MAJOR glaring red flags just for the "chance it does well" we are perpetuating the notion that we are an easy target and we are willing to be bent over so some 19 year old kid can make off with millions of our hard-earned money.

We need to stop allowing ourselves to be exploited for millions of dollars by teams who are anonymous and therefore cannot be held accountable. This is not to say anon teams are inherently bad but it is a step to ensure that somebody's reputation is on the line if they rugged.
